Found it. The chain from `SET`:

**Call chain:** `setCommand`(t_string.c:443)â†’`setGenericCommand`(t_string.c:87)â†’`checkType`(object.c:884)â†’`addReplyErrorObject`(object.c:887)

**Where WRONGTYPE reply is actually written to the client, in the SET path specifically:**

1. **Shared error string is defined once**, at `src/server.c:2203-2204`:
   ```c
   shared.wrongtypeerr = createObject(OBJ_STRING,sdsnew(
       "-WRONGTYPE Operation against a key holding the wrong kind of value\r\n"));
   ```
   This is generic (used by 117 command handlers per the graph, not SET-specific), so this alone isn't "the SET path."

2. **The generic type-check helper**, `checkType()` at `src/object.c:884-891`:
   ```c
   int checkType(client *c, robj *o, int type) {
       if (o && o->type != type) {
           addReplyErrorObject(c,shared.wrongtypeerr);   // <- line 887, sends the reply
           return 1;
       }
       return 0;
   }
   ```

3. **SET-command-specific call sites** â€” `checkType` is invoked from two places that are reached only via the SET command family:
   - `setGenericCommand()` at `src/t_string.c:119`, guarding the new `IFEQ`/`IFNE`/`IFDEQ`/`IFDNE` conditional-SET options (`SET key val IFEQ/IFNE/IFDEQ/IFDNE ...`): checks the type of the *existing* key before comparing values.
     ```c
     kvobj *current = lookupKeyRead(c->db, key);
     if (checkType(c, current, OBJ_STRING)) {   // line 119
         return;
     }
     ```
   - `getGenericCommand()` at `src/t_string.c:467`, reached from `setGenericCommand()` at `src/t_string.c:100` only when the `GET` option is passed (`SET key val GET`), i.e. SET is asked to also return the old value:
     ```c
     if (checkType(c,o,OBJ_STRING)) {   // line 467
         return C_ERR;
     }
     ```

So for plain `SET key value` (no `GET`/`IFEQ`/`IFNE`/`IFDEQ`/`IFDNE`), no type check happens at all â€” SET normally overwrites any existing key regardless of its type. WRONGTYPE only surfaces on SET when one of those options forces a read/compare of the existing value, and in both cases the reply bytes themselves are constructed via the single shared `checkType`â†’`addReplyErrorObject(c, shared.wrongtypeerr)` at `object.c:887`, using the string defined at `server.c:2203-2204`.
